description.narrative:
Despite the difficult context due to the COVID-19 disease and the active presence of armed groups in the project area especially in Djugu, the results achieved this year were satisfactory compared to the first year of implementation. In the second year, the project reached over 8,400 direct beneficiaries.
It should be noted the following results:
- Trócaire carried out two conflict scans during the second year of the project in order to analyze the evolution of conflict dynamics. Three main conflicts were found in the community including (1) land disputes in Mambasa (Banana Ecole, Masisliko, Butiaba) and in Nizi and Lopa in the Territory of Djugu, (2) identity conflicts between pastoralists and farmers, and (3) conflicts related to access to natural resources as follows: water in Lopa and Katoto which affects cohabitation between community members and displaced households, between the artisanal miners and local communities.
- 1,200 households, including 801 women and 399 men, benefited from sustainable livelihood support, including: small livestock (goats), the construction of fish ponds, distribution of food for fish, distribution of vegetable and food crops seeds, …
- To fight against deforestation in the project area and enrich the soil, 35,500 Leucaena seedlings and banana shoots, including 13,900 seedlings in Mambasa and 21,600 in Djugu were produced and distributed to beneficiary households.
- Training sessions and awareness raising sessions were organized on different themes in order to equip beneficiaries with the knowledge that will enable them to carry out their activities : group savings on the sale of products to facilitate the renewal of working tools, management of fish ponds, post-harvest activities (harvest, storage, conservation of agricultural products), management of food and market gardening;
- 1,500 aspirant female leaders, vulnerable women and young girls benefitted from leadership, empowerment and literacy training;
- 12 women leaders, women leaders of citizens' committees were coached on the civil and political rights of women, the right to participate in decision-making and legal provisions guaranteeing the participation of women in order to enable them to effectively assume their responsibilities;
- As part of this intermediate result, the project facilitated access for survivors and people exposed to the risks of SGBV, to specialized psychosocial and legal support through several interventions at the community level and their referral for medical care and socio-economic reintegration;
- The nursing staff of 13 health structures identified in the first year to provide care for survivors in Mambasa were trained to provide psychological care in a non-discriminatory environment;
- Trócaire also strengthened the capacities of implementing partners on conflict sensitivity, conflict analysis and facilitation of community dialogue with the support of the Conflict Sensitivity Technical Advisor. The implementing partners benefit from ongoing technical and financial support.
The emergence of Covid 19 prompted Trócaire and its implementing partners to adapt the project according to the context. To this end, funds were reallocated with Embassy authorization to the organization to Covid19 prevention activities.
